WEBVTT

1
00:00:11.950 --> 00:00:13.950
you can find me on  and pless support me
https://www.youtube.com/@titoGamersHaven

2
00:00:13.970 --> 00:00:15.980
[intriguing music playing]

3
00:00:24.980 --> 00:00:28.860
[Ben] <i>Someone once asked me
what universe this was.</i>

4
00:00:28.860 --> 00:00:30.530
<i>A strange question that</i>

5
00:00:30.530 --> 00:00:32.950
<i>stuck with me all these years later.</i>

6
00:00:32.950 --> 00:00:34.530
<i>All I could say for sure</i>

7
00:00:34.540 --> 00:00:37.580
<i>was it was the only one I knew of.</i>

8
00:00:37.580 --> 00:00:40.040
<i>And that was as true then as it is now.</i>

9
00:00:42.080 --> 00:00:44.590
<i>Am I an extraordinary man?</i>

10
00:00:44.590 --> 00:00:46.170
<i>Yes.</i>

11
00:00:46.170 --> 00:00:47.840
<i>Am I an ordinary man?</i>

12
00:00:47.840 --> 00:00:49.260
<i>Yes.</i>

13
00:00:49.260 --> 00:00:51.550
<i>I'm both. I'm neither.</i>

14
00:00:51.550 --> 00:00:53.220
<i>But aren't we all?</i>

15
00:00:55.510 --> 00:00:57.020
<i>New York.</i>

16
00:00:59.890 --> 00:01:01.900
<i>I grew up in this city.</i>

17
00:01:03.400 --> 00:01:04.940
<i>- I learned to fight in this city.</i>
- [kids grunting]

18
00:01:04.940 --> 00:01:06.440
Get him!

19
00:01:07.780 --> 00:01:09.780
[Ben] <i>And I fell in love in this city.</i>

20
00:01:13.370 --> 00:01:15.370
<i>A mistake I'll never make again.</i>

21
00:01:18.620 --> 00:01:20.710
<i>I used to be The Spider.</i>

22
00:01:20.710 --> 00:01:22.790
<i>this city's hero.</i>

23
00:01:22.790 --> 00:01:24.000
<i>Always on guard.</i>

24
00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:26.880
<i>always ready to swoop in
and save the day.</i>

25
00:01:27.710 --> 00:01:28.840
[grunting]

26
00:01:44.230 --> 00:01:46.610
<i>That ended when Ruby died.</i>

27
00:01:58.790 --> 00:02:01.790
<i>We were going to be married in the spring.</i>

28
00:02:01.790 --> 00:02:04.580
<i>I even bought a ring to make it official.</i>

29
00:02:04.580 --> 00:02:07.840
<i>A ring I never had the chance to give her.</i>

30
00:02:16.100 --> 00:02:18.050
<i>Ruby once told me that</i>

31
00:02:18.060 --> 00:02:22.100
<i>with great power
comes great responsibility.</i>

32
00:02:22.100 --> 00:02:24.440
<i>Well. she was the greatest responsibility</i>

33
00:02:24.440 --> 00:02:26.520
<i>I ever had.</i>

34
00:02:26.520 --> 00:02:28.520
<i>And I failed her.</i>

35
00:02:30.230 --> 00:02:32.240
<i>The Spider failed her.</i>

36
00:02:35.530 --> 00:02:38.740
<i>After that. I didn't want
the power or the responsibility.</i>

37
00:02:42.750 --> 00:02:45.540
<i>So I went back to being
just an ordinary man.</i>

38
00:02:47.750 --> 00:02:50.130
<i>That was five years ago.</i>

39
00:02:55.380 --> 00:02:57.390
[♪ Kirby sings "Saving Grace"]

40
00:03:04.730 --> 00:03:07.400
<i>♪ The colors fading from the photograph ♪</i>

41
00:03:07.400 --> 00:03:09.150
<i>♪ I could tell the story ♪</i>

42
00:03:09.150 --> 00:03:11.820
<i>♪ but still you wouldn't know the half ♪</i>

43
00:03:11.820 --> 00:03:14.610
<i>♪ This love was brought to life
from shards of glass ♪</i>

44
00:03:14.610 --> 00:03:16.700
<i>♪ When you kiss me there's a shifting ♪</i>

45
00:03:16.700 --> 00:03:19.160
<i>♪ in the sepia tone ♪</i>

46
00:03:19.160 --> 00:03:22.370
<i>♪ Can't escape the madness.
baby. magnetism ♪</i>

47
00:03:22.370 --> 00:03:25.710
<i>♪ Run away but something
pulls me back into it ♪</i>

48
00:03:25.710 --> 00:03:28.830
<i>♪ Lately I've been staring
at a broken mirror ♪</i>

49
00:03:28.830 --> 00:03:32.300
<i>♪ Needing someone to call my own ♪</i>

50
00:03:32.300 --> 00:03:35.510
<i>♪ Hey. lover ♪</i>

51
00:03:35.510 --> 00:03:38.380
<i>♪ I need someone to save me now ♪</i>

52
00:03:38.390 --> 00:03:40.640
<i>♪ from all the pain ♪</i>

53
00:03:40.640 --> 00:03:43.100
<i>♪ I suffer ♪</i>

54
00:03:43.100 --> 00:03:45.930
<i>♪ and the heavy world
that weighs me down ♪</i>

55
00:03:45.940 --> 00:03:49.480
<i>♪ 'Cause the world ain't sweet ♪</i>

56
00:03:49.480 --> 00:03:51.860
<i>♪ It's bitter to taste ♪</i>

57
00:03:51.860 --> 00:03:53.230
<i>♪ But you could be ♪</i>

58
00:03:53.230 --> 00:03:56.450
<i>♪ my saving grace ♪</i>

59
00:04:17.800 --> 00:04:19.800
[song ends]

60
00:04:22.050 --> 00:04:24.140
- [piano playing up-tempo jazz]
- [match strikes]

61
00:04:24.140 --> 00:04:26.140
[quiet. indistinct chatter]

62
00:04:39.070 --> 00:04:40.570
What do you think?

63
00:04:45.120 --> 00:04:47.040
[woman] I think you got a bingo.

64
00:04:47.040 --> 00:04:48.960
Say. you're kinda handsome.

65
00:04:48.960 --> 00:04:50.710
Now I'm questioning your eyesight.

66
00:04:50.710 --> 00:04:51.790
[chuckles]

67
00:04:51.790 --> 00:04:53.130
Funny. too.

68
00:04:53.130 --> 00:04:55.380
So. you got a wife?

69
00:04:55.380 --> 00:04:57.710
- No.
- Shame.

70
00:04:57.720 --> 00:04:59.170
I got a husband.

71
00:04:59.170 --> 00:05:01.340
Not that it's ever stopped me
from having a good time.

72
00:05:01.340 --> 00:05:02.340
Know what I mean?

73
00:05:02.340 --> 00:05:04.430
I've got a decent idea.

74
00:05:04.430 --> 00:05:07.430
When your husband gets the same idea.
tell him to give me a call.

75
00:05:08.480 --> 00:05:10.100
[woman] Hm. Okay.

76
00:05:13.940 --> 00:05:15.610
[busboy] Excuse me. sir? Sir!

77
00:05:16.610 --> 00:05:17.780
You forgot your hat.

78
00:05:17.780 --> 00:05:19.070
Thank you.

79
00:05:20.150 --> 00:05:23.610
You keep following me.
it won't end the way you want it to.

80
00:05:23.620 --> 00:05:25.410
It never does.

81
00:05:27.080 --> 00:05:28.490
Addison!

82
00:05:28.500 --> 00:05:29.950
[cars honking]

83
00:05:29.960 --> 00:05:31.870
[thrilling music playing]

84
00:05:42.430 --> 00:05:43.390
[grunts]

85
00:05:49.480 --> 00:05:51.680
Sorry. pal. Hey.

86
00:05:51.690 --> 00:05:53.480
Don't do it. Addison.

87
00:05:53.480 --> 00:05:56.270
I'm as liable to shoot you
as I am to give chase.

88
00:05:59.150 --> 00:06:00.860
Damn it!

89
00:06:08.790 --> 00:06:10.200
[people chattering]

90
00:06:10.200 --> 00:06:11.830
[woman] Oh. my God. is he dead?

91
00:06:15.790 --> 00:06:17.290
- [gasps]
- [onlookers exclaim]

92
00:06:18.880 --> 00:06:20.760
- [grunts]
- Sir. sir. you shouldn't--

93
00:06:20.760 --> 00:06:22.930
- You really shouldn't--
- Where did they go? Which way?

94
00:06:49.830 --> 00:06:51.450
[high-pitched ringing]

95
00:06:51.450 --> 00:06:54.000
[distorted. muffled voice speaking]

96
00:06:58.130 --> 00:07:01.710
[man] It's not my fault you ripped off
the wrong people. Addison.

97
00:07:01.710 --> 00:07:05.130
Now. come on. let's go. It's getting late
and it smells like shit back here.

98
00:07:05.130 --> 00:07:06.800
I tried to warn you.

99
00:07:07.800 --> 00:07:09.300
What?

100
00:07:10.350 --> 00:07:11.310
Whoa.

101
00:07:17.730 --> 00:07:19.860
Now you're gonna burn.

102
00:07:27.910 --> 00:07:29.870
Jesus. Mary and Joseph.

103
00:07:29.870 --> 00:07:31.580
- [grunting]
- [whimpering]

104
00:07:35.620 --> 00:07:38.620
Oh… Oh. no. Oh. my God! Oh...

105
00:07:38.630 --> 00:07:41.000
Whoa. whoa! [grunts]

106
00:07:43.630 --> 00:07:45.130
[Ben grunting]

107
00:08:03.150 --> 00:08:04.610
Huh.

108
00:08:10.740 --> 00:08:12.620
Okay.

109
00:08:12.620 --> 00:08:16.160
[exclaims]
Oh! That man was completely on fire.

110
00:08:16.160 --> 00:08:18.160
I've never seen such a thing.

111
00:08:18.170 --> 00:08:20.830
Should've known it was fishy
they offered me 50 bucks

112
00:08:20.830 --> 00:08:22.000
to track down a nobody.

113
00:08:22.000 --> 00:08:24.210
Who hired you-- guy named Winston?

114
00:08:24.210 --> 00:08:26.720
- Yeah.
- Bastard only offered me 30.

115
00:08:28.680 --> 00:08:30.340
I need a drink. You?

116
00:08:30.340 --> 00:08:33.010
Sure. Nothing too fancy. All I got is--

117
00:08:33.010 --> 00:08:34.140
Three bucks.

118
00:08:34.140 --> 00:08:37.430
Come on. Donegal. I know a joint. [grunts]

119
00:08:37.430 --> 00:08:41.060
Might even have a girl for you.
If you like train wrecks.

120
00:08:41.060 --> 00:08:43.520
Oh. I must.

121
00:08:43.520 --> 00:08:45.530
'cause I keep marrying 'em.

122
00:08:51.070 --> 00:08:52.200
Morning.

123
00:08:52.200 --> 00:08:53.620
It was.

124
00:08:53.620 --> 00:08:55.790
Now it's a mediocre afternoon.
headed towards

125
00:08:55.790 --> 00:08:58.000
a lousy evening. Coffee?

126
00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:00.290
You got anything a little harder?

127
00:09:00.290 --> 00:09:02.120
That's what I keep asking my husband.

128
00:09:02.130 --> 00:09:04.250
- You can just pour it right in.
- That's just it--

129
00:09:04.250 --> 00:09:05.500
you really can't.

130
00:09:05.500 --> 00:09:06.800
- Any calls?
- Well. to receive calls.

131
00:09:06.800 --> 00:09:09.090
you got to pay Ma Bell.

132
00:09:09.090 --> 00:09:11.180
Till then. that's just a paperweight.

133
00:09:11.180 --> 00:09:12.470
How'd it go with Addison?

134
00:09:14.140 --> 00:09:16.140
Oh. wow. That well. huh?

135
00:09:17.770 --> 00:09:19.180
Addison's dead.

136
00:09:19.180 --> 00:09:20.390
- You...
- No.

137
00:09:20.390 --> 00:09:24.270
- Some other guy. This goddamn city--
- [door opens]

138
00:09:24.270 --> 00:09:25.520
You open?

139
00:09:25.520 --> 00:09:26.900
- No!
- Yes!

140
00:09:26.900 --> 00:09:28.400
I tried calling. but it didn't

141
00:09:28.400 --> 00:09:30.360
- seem to go through.
- Mr.-Mr. Reilly believes that

142
00:09:30.360 --> 00:09:32.360
business is better conducted face-to-face.

143
00:09:32.360 --> 00:09:34.620
Wouldn't you agree. Mister…?

144
00:09:34.620 --> 00:09:35.570
Uh. Carmedy.

145
00:09:35.580 --> 00:09:37.080
Right this way. Mr. Carmedy.

146
00:09:38.540 --> 00:09:39.870
It's about my wife.

147
00:09:50.840 --> 00:09:53.720
You a rich man. Mr. Carmedy?

148
00:09:53.720 --> 00:09:56.640
No. Not particularly.

149
00:09:56.640 --> 00:09:58.520
Possessed of a keen wit. then?

150
00:09:59.310 --> 00:10:00.310
Huh?

151
00:10:01.560 --> 00:10:02.640
Huh.

152
00:10:02.640 --> 00:10:04.940
Look. I heard my wife
on the phone this afternoon.

153
00:10:04.940 --> 00:10:07.820
She's gonna meet
this so-and-so at 8:00 tonight.

154
00:10:07.820 --> 00:10:10.280
I even got the address. Look. look. look.

155
00:10:10.280 --> 00:10:13.150
I do love a client who comes prepared.

156
00:10:13.160 --> 00:10:15.280
So you'll do it? You'll take the case?

157
00:10:15.280 --> 00:10:17.620
Okay. Carmedy.
my rate's ten dollars a day. plus--

158
00:10:17.620 --> 00:10:19.910
But you'll get pictures. right?

159
00:10:19.910 --> 00:10:23.330
Cause without pictures it's basically
just a-a "he said. she said" situation.

160
00:10:23.330 --> 00:10:25.960
I'm sure your suspicions are unfounded.
Mr. Carmedy.

161
00:10:25.960 --> 00:10:28.790
but if it comes to it. don't you fret.
Ben's an ace photographer.

162
00:10:28.800 --> 00:10:29.710
Never miss a shot.

163
00:10:32.420 --> 00:10:34.010
Ten dollars a day.

164
00:10:34.010 --> 00:10:35.680
Plus expenses.

165
00:10:35.680 --> 00:10:38.220
Janet'll get your info
and a small retainer.

166
00:10:38.220 --> 00:10:40.850
Come back day after tomorrow
and. uh… [clears throat]

167
00:10:40.850 --> 00:10:41.970
I'll give you what you want.

168
00:10:41.980 --> 00:10:44.520
[exclaims softly] Thank you. [chuckles]

169
00:10:44.520 --> 00:10:45.730
[chuckles softly] Come on. Mr. Carmedy.

170
00:10:45.730 --> 00:10:47.020
let's get that info
and that retainer. huh?

171
00:10:47.020 --> 00:10:48.980
[Carmedy laughs]

172
00:10:48.980 --> 00:10:50.480
[quirky music playing]

173
00:10:51.570 --> 00:10:55.240
Explosion at Standard Oil.
Read all about it.

174
00:10:55.240 --> 00:10:58.530
Explosion at Standard Oil.

175
00:10:58.530 --> 00:11:02.330
Explosion. here. at Standard Oil.

176
00:11:15.550 --> 00:11:17.640
- [entry bells jingle]
- [door closes]

177
00:11:17.640 --> 00:11:20.050
Sorry I'm late. I was chasing a story.

178
00:11:20.060 --> 00:11:21.430
Some other mobster

179
00:11:21.430 --> 00:11:24.930
is finally making a move on Silvermane.

180
00:11:24.940 --> 00:11:26.850
Burned down his mansion
a couple of nights ago.

181
00:11:26.850 --> 00:11:28.350
killed six of his men.

182
00:11:28.360 --> 00:11:31.110
and somehow.
the old bastard escaped.

183
00:11:31.110 --> 00:11:33.530
You think Finn Byrne
likes being called Silvermane?

184
00:11:33.530 --> 00:11:36.860
Thinks it speaks to-- I don't know--
gravitas and longevity?

185
00:11:36.860 --> 00:11:39.370
[short chuckle]
If I ever get that rich. you call me

186
00:11:39.370 --> 00:11:41.950
- anything you want.
- That-That's a used pickle. Uh...

187
00:11:43.540 --> 00:11:45.290
So. what you hiding over there--
another cheating spouse?

188
00:11:48.420 --> 00:11:49.710
Thought you said you weren't gonna
take those anymore.

189
00:11:49.710 --> 00:11:52.550
I haven't paid Janet in months.
Beggars can't be choosers.

190
00:11:52.550 --> 00:11:56.380
Says the man who has chosen
to be a beggar. For Chrissakes. Ben--

191
00:11:56.380 --> 00:11:58.300
Robbie. not today. okay? Not again.

192
00:12:00.180 --> 00:12:01.890
Have you seen it out there?

193
00:12:01.890 --> 00:12:03.470
The city's a mess.

194
00:12:03.470 --> 00:12:05.560
Ever since The Spider disappeared.

195
00:12:05.560 --> 00:12:08.140
Silvermane's got this city by the throat.

196
00:12:08.150 --> 00:12:09.730
Crime is out of control

197
00:12:09.730 --> 00:12:12.480
and the police
are completely in his pocket.

198
00:12:12.480 --> 00:12:13.770
Now. the people--

199
00:12:13.780 --> 00:12:16.360
the people could use a hero.

200
00:12:19.820 --> 00:12:21.570
Well...

201
00:12:21.580 --> 00:12:23.280
I hope they find someone.

202
00:12:23.290 --> 00:12:26.120
- You used to be--
- I know who I used to be.

203
00:12:28.670 --> 00:12:31.630
And I know who I am now.

204
00:12:31.630 --> 00:12:34.590
There's always gonna
be another Silvermane. Robbie.

205
00:12:34.590 --> 00:12:36.050
There's no point in fighting it.

206
00:12:37.090 --> 00:12:40.130
I can't help but wonder what Ruby would
think if she heard you talking like that.

207
00:12:40.140 --> 00:12:41.470
[dramatic music playing]

208
00:12:41.470 --> 00:12:43.430
[muffled grunting]

209
00:12:53.270 --> 00:12:55.280
Ruby's been dead a long time.

210
00:12:57.360 --> 00:12:59.530
I don't care what she'd think anymore.

211
00:13:06.080 --> 00:13:08.080
Hey. Frankie. you're out early today.

212
00:13:08.080 --> 00:13:10.830
Hey. Reilly. how you doing?

213
00:13:13.880 --> 00:13:16.130
You know. I've been
practicing my pocket tricks.

214
00:13:16.130 --> 00:13:18.260
[Ben] Oh. yeah? How's that going?

215
00:13:19.670 --> 00:13:22.140
[Frankie] You tell me. [wolf whistles]

216
00:13:24.760 --> 00:13:25.930
Dames. huh?

217
00:13:25.930 --> 00:13:27.100
What would you know?

218
00:13:27.100 --> 00:13:29.100
Lots. I'm wise behind these ears.

219
00:13:29.100 --> 00:13:31.060
Smarts like that.
maybe think about going to school.

220
00:13:31.060 --> 00:13:33.600
Who needs it? A plus B equals C.

221
00:13:33.610 --> 00:13:35.690
- You don't do math with letters. kid.
- [line ringing]

222
00:13:35.690 --> 00:13:37.230
Donegal. Reilly.

223
00:13:37.230 --> 00:13:39.530
Listen. I think we should
talk about last night.

224
00:13:40.780 --> 00:13:43.200
[Donegal] <i>So. what's this proposition
you got for me?</i>

225
00:13:43.200 --> 00:13:45.160
We left a man dead last night.

226
00:13:45.160 --> 00:13:47.410
Feels like that could be trouble
coming down the tracks

227
00:13:47.410 --> 00:13:50.250
or an opportunity worth pursuing.
Either way.

228
00:13:50.250 --> 00:13:52.040
I think we should know more
about who hired us

229
00:13:52.040 --> 00:13:54.080
and why they wanted him so bad.

230
00:13:57.170 --> 00:13:58.300
So you got a plan. then?

231
00:13:59.380 --> 00:14:02.510
Kinda.
Can you be sober by 9:00 a.m. tomorrow?

232
00:14:02.510 --> 00:14:05.800
Oh. hi. handsome. Long time no see.

233
00:14:07.100 --> 00:14:08.510
By the morning?

234
00:14:08.520 --> 00:14:10.060
Mm... sure.

235
00:14:11.770 --> 00:14:13.270
[newsie shouting] <i>Get your
evening edition.</i>

236
00:14:13.270 --> 00:14:15.900
Silvermane survives in skivvies.

237
00:14:15.900 --> 00:14:17.400
Thank you. sir.

238
00:14:17.400 --> 00:14:19.570
Hot off the presses.

239
00:14:19.570 --> 00:14:22.030
<i>Silvermane survives in skivvies.</i>

240
00:14:22.030 --> 00:14:24.070
[Robbie] <i>Ever since
The Spider disappeared.</i>

241
00:14:24.070 --> 00:14:26.950
<i>Silvermane has had
a chokehold on this city.</i>

242
00:14:26.950 --> 00:14:29.830
<i>murdering anyone that gets in his way.</i>

243
00:14:29.830 --> 00:14:32.290
<i>But one brave soul tried to free us</i>

244
00:14:32.290 --> 00:14:34.330
<i>from the mobster's reign of terror.</i>

245
00:14:34.330 --> 00:14:36.380
<i>setting fire to Silvermane's mansion</i>

246
00:14:36.380 --> 00:14:38.670
<i>while he was asleep upstairs.</i>

247
00:14:38.670 --> 00:14:40.800
<i>But he failed to kill the old bastard.</i>

248
00:14:40.800 --> 00:14:43.050
<i>so brace yourself for a bloody rampage</i>

249
00:14:43.050 --> 00:14:45.380
<i>from Silvermane and his goons.</i>

250
00:14:45.390 --> 00:14:47.550
<i>If only The Spider were here</i>

251
00:14:47.550 --> 00:14:49.510
<i>to save us from the madness.</i>

252
00:14:49.510 --> 00:14:51.680
Damn. Robbie.

253
00:14:51.680 --> 00:14:53.690
Give it a rest. would you?

254
00:14:58.520 --> 00:15:00.530
[contemplative music playing]

255
00:15:12.790 --> 00:15:14.790
♪ ♪

256
00:15:32.810 --> 00:15:35.230
Evening. sir. How can I help you?

257
00:15:35.230 --> 00:15:38.020
I got a delivery for Boris Karloff.

258
00:15:38.020 --> 00:15:40.020
[doorman] Sorry. bud.
Karloff don't live here.

259
00:15:40.020 --> 00:15:43.190
[Ben] No. sure he does.
He might be listed under his stage name.

260
00:15:43.190 --> 00:15:44.860
Uh. Stein.

261
00:15:45.990 --> 00:15:49.450
Frank N. Stein.

262
00:15:50.660 --> 00:15:51.870
[elevator bell dings]

263
00:15:51.870 --> 00:15:54.910
All right. Don't bother.
I'll see myself out.

264
00:16:07.050 --> 00:16:08.550
[sighs]

265
00:16:10.930 --> 00:16:12.510
[grunts]

266
00:16:12.510 --> 00:16:14.520
[panting]

267
00:16:26.070 --> 00:16:28.070
[grunting]

268
00:16:30.120 --> 00:16:32.200
[grunting]

269
00:16:39.830 --> 00:16:42.250
[man chuckling inside]

270
00:16:45.960 --> 00:16:47.970
[indistinct conversation]

271
00:17:10.320 --> 00:17:11.450
[woman] No. stop.

272
00:17:11.450 --> 00:17:13.570
- [man] Come on... Come on.
- No.

273
00:17:13.580 --> 00:17:14.620
[man] Gimme something.

274
00:17:14.620 --> 00:17:16.660
[woman] Get off of me!

275
00:17:16.660 --> 00:17:18.290
[man] Come here!

276
00:17:18.290 --> 00:17:19.620
[kissing]

277
00:17:19.620 --> 00:17:20.920
- [grunts]
- Oh!

278
00:17:21.960 --> 00:17:22.790
[thwip]

279
00:17:24.290 --> 00:17:26.000
What the hell?

280
00:17:42.770 --> 00:17:44.100
He's here early.

281
00:17:44.110 --> 00:17:45.940
[whispering] You're late.

282
00:17:45.940 --> 00:17:47.900
Go. Go.

283
00:17:50.450 --> 00:17:52.030
Morning. Winston.

284
00:17:52.030 --> 00:17:54.410
Care for a cup of coffee
or maybe some tea

285
00:17:54.410 --> 00:17:57.370
or do you just want to order both
and see which one comes first?

286
00:17:57.370 --> 00:17:59.120
Save your breath. Reilly.

287
00:17:59.120 --> 00:18:00.700
You told me you know where Addison is.

288
00:18:00.710 --> 00:18:02.660
so take your money and talk.

289
00:18:02.670 --> 00:18:04.920
Actually. the price has gone up.

290
00:18:04.920 --> 00:18:06.250
Excuse me?

291
00:18:07.170 --> 00:18:09.800
The other PI you hired
told me offered him 50.

292
00:18:09.800 --> 00:18:12.510
so I'm not telling you
for a penny less than 200.

293
00:18:12.510 --> 00:18:14.840
Cute.

294
00:18:14.840 --> 00:18:16.890
But give me one good reason
I shouldn't plug you.

295
00:18:16.890 --> 00:18:18.970
[suspenseful music playing]

296
00:18:18.970 --> 00:18:20.390
How about 38 reasons?

297
00:18:20.390 --> 00:18:22.270
- [gun cocks]
- It's actually a .32.

298
00:18:22.270 --> 00:18:25.100
but I doubt your organs
will know the difference.

299
00:18:25.100 --> 00:18:27.940
Now. a guy like you in a suit like that--

300
00:18:27.940 --> 00:18:30.400
you didn't cook this up on your own.

301
00:18:30.400 --> 00:18:33.570
So. why don't you go back
to whoever it is that sent you

302
00:18:33.570 --> 00:18:34.990
and find me 200 dollars.

303
00:18:34.990 --> 00:18:36.870
And then I'll tell you where Addison is.

304
00:18:36.870 --> 00:18:39.740
- And I'll keep the .30 as a tip.
- [clears throat]

305
00:18:39.740 --> 00:18:42.540
Janet'll keep the .30 as a tip.

306
00:18:42.540 --> 00:18:43.870
Cute.

307
00:18:45.120 --> 00:18:46.380
Real cute.

308
00:18:57.930 --> 00:18:59.930
[engine starts]

309
00:19:10.230 --> 00:19:12.240
♪ ♪

310
00:19:36.470 --> 00:19:38.470
♪ ♪

311
00:19:53.230 --> 00:19:55.110
[soft chuckle]

312
00:19:55.110 --> 00:19:56.700
Funny.

313
00:19:56.700 --> 00:19:58.860
Guy burns down my house.

314
00:19:58.870 --> 00:20:00.910
tries to kill me...

315
00:20:00.910 --> 00:20:02.660
Makes me feel young again.

316
00:20:03.830 --> 00:20:06.250
Did Reilly tell you where Addison is?

317
00:20:06.250 --> 00:20:07.870
[Winston] A shakedown.

318
00:20:07.870 --> 00:20:11.040
He won't tell me where Addison is
unless he gets more cash.

319
00:20:11.040 --> 00:20:12.420
[Silvermane] Pay him whatever he wants.

320
00:20:13.500 --> 00:20:16.720
The boys are convinced
Addison's got some kind of powers.

321
00:20:21.010 --> 00:20:23.850
If he does. I want to talk to him.

322
00:20:23.850 --> 00:20:25.470
Do whatever it takes.

323
00:20:25.480 --> 00:20:27.140
Find Addison.

324
00:20:33.730 --> 00:20:35.780
Hot damn! Can you believe our luck?

325
00:20:36.860 --> 00:20:39.910
Sadly. yes.
Stepping into a steaming pile of dogshit

326
00:20:39.910 --> 00:20:41.740
is kind of my specialty.

327
00:20:41.740 --> 00:20:44.370
Are you daft?
Byrne's the deepest pockets in New York.

328
00:20:44.370 --> 00:20:46.200
We're the only ones
who know Addison's dead.

329
00:20:46.200 --> 00:20:47.620
We can ask for a thousand now.

330
00:20:47.620 --> 00:20:49.750
Shake down Silvermane? It's an idea.

331
00:20:49.750 --> 00:20:52.880
Thing is. I've got
this crazy preference for being alive.

332
00:20:52.880 --> 00:20:54.960
You do what you want.
I'm leaving this one alone.

333
00:20:54.960 --> 00:20:58.590
You're a coward. Reilly.
Fortune favors the bold.

334
00:20:58.590 --> 00:21:00.510
- And look how poor I am.
- [laughs]

335
00:21:05.560 --> 00:21:07.140
[Janet in distance] I'm in here.

336
00:21:08.430 --> 00:21:09.520
[door opens]

337
00:21:09.520 --> 00:21:10.730
How'd that go?

338
00:21:10.730 --> 00:21:12.230
- [Ben] Dead end.
- [door closes]

339
00:21:12.230 --> 00:21:13.440
How about this?

340
00:21:13.440 --> 00:21:15.980
[clicks tongue] Uh... interesting.

341
00:21:15.980 --> 00:21:17.070
You got some great shots.

342
00:21:17.070 --> 00:21:19.490
- [Ben chuckles] I couldn't resist.
- [chuckles]

343
00:21:20.950 --> 00:21:22.740
I do have one question. though.

344
00:21:22.740 --> 00:21:25.660
Am I crazy or is that
the goddamn mayor of New York?

345
00:21:25.660 --> 00:21:28.950
[ominous music playing]

346
00:21:28.960 --> 00:21:31.210
[mayor over speakers] <i>I believe in you.</i>

347
00:21:31.210 --> 00:21:34.000
<i>the hardworking man
trying to earn a decent living.</i>

348
00:21:34.000 --> 00:21:37.550
<i>I believe in you. the dedicated woman.</i>

349
00:21:37.550 --> 00:21:40.340
<i>Our city has hit hard times.</i>

350
00:21:40.340 --> 00:21:42.220
<i>We've lost our heroes.</i>

351
00:21:42.220 --> 00:21:44.890
<i>It feels like no one is coming to help us.</i>

352
00:21:44.890 --> 00:21:47.760
<i>But I believe we can
be our own heroes. together.</i>

353
00:21:47.770 --> 00:21:49.930
[Carmedy] You sure
she didn't meet up with anybody?

354
00:21:49.930 --> 00:21:52.440
Like I said. your... wife

355
00:21:52.440 --> 00:21:54.600
was alone the entire night.

356
00:21:54.610 --> 00:21:57.820
What about 8:00 p.m.? The-the Redcliff?
What was that all about?

357
00:21:57.820 --> 00:22:00.110
Come on. Carmedy. smile.
This is great news.

358
00:22:00.110 --> 00:22:02.820
- No. I-I know. I know. I just...
- I get it.

359
00:22:02.820 --> 00:22:04.740
- Marriage can be a terrifying endeavor.
- Oh...

360
00:22:04.740 --> 00:22:07.120
opening yourself up
to another person like that.

361
00:22:07.120 --> 00:22:08.660
making yourself vulnerable.

362
00:22:08.660 --> 00:22:10.450
I don't even feel good
about taking your money.

363
00:22:10.460 --> 00:22:11.870
- [Carmedy] Really?
- Yeah.

364
00:22:11.870 --> 00:22:14.580
Go home. Carmedy.
You have a beautiful…[laughs]

365
00:22:14.580 --> 00:22:16.420
- and loyal wife.
- Oh.

366
00:22:16.420 --> 00:22:19.000
You know how loyal she is.

367
00:22:19.010 --> 00:22:21.130
- I-I...
- You're a very lucky man.

368
00:22:21.130 --> 00:22:22.630
- Yeah?
- Now go home.

369
00:22:22.630 --> 00:22:24.380
[chuckles weakly] Uh...

370
00:22:24.390 --> 00:22:26.640
- [door closes]
- We needed that money.

371
00:22:26.640 --> 00:22:30.140
I don't know if you're aware.
but there's a Depression going on.

372
00:22:30.140 --> 00:22:33.230
I'm aware. but whatever that was.
I want nothing to do with it.

373
00:22:33.230 --> 00:22:34.230
Who do you think he was?

374
00:22:34.230 --> 00:22:36.310
Who knows?
Someone trying to smear the mayor.

375
00:22:36.310 --> 00:22:38.400
And that woman--
if she's not Mrs. Carmedy.

376
00:22:38.400 --> 00:22:40.150
then who the hell is she?

377
00:22:40.150 --> 00:22:41.740
The only thing I can say
with any certainty

378
00:22:41.740 --> 00:22:44.490
is she isn't married
to that syphilitic walrus.

379
00:22:44.490 --> 00:22:46.070
[groans]

380
00:22:46.070 --> 00:22:48.490
[muffled pulsing. warbling]

381
00:22:51.700 --> 00:22:54.620
Another headache. huh?
That sixth sense thing?

382
00:22:55.540 --> 00:22:57.130
You should listen to it.

383
00:22:57.130 --> 00:22:58.840
Long as I've known you
it's never steered you wrong.

384
00:22:58.840 --> 00:23:01.960
I'd love to. Trouble is I'm not currently
sure what it's trying to tell me.

385
00:23:02.670 --> 00:23:03.720
Hang on.

386
00:23:04.800 --> 00:23:06.050
Oh. I can hear it.

387
00:23:06.930 --> 00:23:08.260
It's saying...

388
00:23:08.260 --> 00:23:11.140
"Pay your secretary." Except you can't.

389
00:23:11.140 --> 00:23:13.390
'cause you just gave away the only money
we've made all month.

390
00:23:13.390 --> 00:23:14.310
You're at the top of my list.

391
00:23:14.310 --> 00:23:16.810
Yeah. well. you better
do something about it soon.

392
00:23:16.810 --> 00:23:19.270
I just interviewed
for a sales position at Gimbels.

393
00:23:19.270 --> 00:23:22.030
Blame my husband.
He has this annoying habit

394
00:23:22.030 --> 00:23:24.240
of demanding food on a daily basis.

395
00:23:27.820 --> 00:23:30.450
What about selling the photographs
to the woman?

396
00:23:30.450 --> 00:23:32.490
You want to steer clear of the mayor.
that's fine.

397
00:23:32.500 --> 00:23:35.460
but maybe
there's still some cash to be had.

398
00:23:35.460 --> 00:23:36.960
[mischievous music playing]

399
00:23:36.960 --> 00:23:39.250
Blackmail. huh?

400
00:23:39.250 --> 00:23:40.840
That's not a terrible idea.

401
00:23:40.840 --> 00:23:42.380
- It's not a good idea.
- Ah.

402
00:23:42.380 --> 00:23:44.130
but it's not a terrible idea.

403
00:23:44.130 --> 00:23:46.050
[Robbie] <i>Yeah. I shit you not.</i>

404
00:23:46.050 --> 00:23:47.930
she had me covered in whipped cream
all the way up to here.

405
00:23:47.930 --> 00:23:51.930
[chuckles] Girl. Robbie'll do anything
to get the story.

406
00:23:51.930 --> 00:23:54.220
Jesus. you look like shit.

407
00:23:54.230 --> 00:23:55.600
More than usual. is what I'm saying.

408
00:23:55.600 --> 00:23:57.850
- Nice to see you. too.
- [Robbie] <i>What's so important</i>

409
00:23:57.850 --> 00:23:59.600
it couldn't wait
till I was back downtown?

410
00:23:59.610 --> 00:24:01.610
Any chance you know who this is?

411
00:24:02.400 --> 00:24:04.940
[Robbie] Ah. you must be joking.

412
00:24:04.940 --> 00:24:06.280
Oh. that's Cat Hardy.

413
00:24:06.280 --> 00:24:08.570
Back in the day.
you wouldn't have had to ask.

414
00:24:10.870 --> 00:24:12.870
Five minutes. Drawer three.

415
00:24:15.790 --> 00:24:17.460
What are you looking for. anyway?

416
00:24:17.460 --> 00:24:20.670
Uh. some poor sap
got knocked off a few nights ago.

417
00:24:20.670 --> 00:24:23.340
Friend gave me a tip
something's off with the body.

418
00:24:23.340 --> 00:24:24.840
Might be a story in it.

419
00:24:26.920 --> 00:24:29.130
Say. uh. you might want to look away.

420
00:24:29.140 --> 00:24:32.220
Any idea where I can find
this Cat Hardy lady?

421
00:24:32.220 --> 00:24:33.930
[Robbie] Oh. yeah.

422
00:24:33.930 --> 00:24:36.850
Now. she is the star attraction
over at The Alcove.

423
00:24:39.150 --> 00:24:42.190
Huh. That is weird.

424
00:24:43.480 --> 00:24:46.320
Say. does this look like
a guy who died in a fire to you?

425
00:24:47.780 --> 00:24:50.990
[Ben] No. but he sure as hell did.
I was there.

426
00:24:52.490 --> 00:24:53.450
And?

427
00:24:53.450 --> 00:24:55.290
They ID him yet?

428
00:24:55.290 --> 00:24:56.750
[Robbie] James Addison.

429
00:24:56.750 --> 00:24:58.710
Shit.

430
00:24:58.710 --> 00:25:00.120
So. if they know. the cops'll know.

431
00:25:00.120 --> 00:25:03.170
and then Silvermane will know
that Donegal is trying to rip him off.

432
00:25:03.170 --> 00:25:05.380
Do me a favor. Hold off on printing that.

433
00:25:05.380 --> 00:25:07.880
I want to warn a friend
before he gets himself killed.

434
00:25:07.880 --> 00:25:09.260
[groans]

435
00:25:09.930 --> 00:25:12.760
What? It's just a migraine. [groans]

436
00:25:12.760 --> 00:25:14.140
[muffled pulsing. warbling]

437
00:25:15.180 --> 00:25:16.350
[groans]

438
00:25:16.350 --> 00:25:18.560
[foreboding music playing]

439
00:25:18.560 --> 00:25:20.350
What's going on. Ben?

440
00:25:20.350 --> 00:25:21.850
Did this guy have super powers?

441
00:25:25.610 --> 00:25:26.900
Is he like you?

442
00:25:27.990 --> 00:25:31.200
Forget about it. Robbie. He's dead.

443
00:25:33.530 --> 00:25:35.240
<i>Did Donegal say when he'd be back?</i>

444
00:25:35.240 --> 00:25:36.660
[bartender] <i>He didn't say shit.</i>

445
00:25:36.660 --> 00:25:39.290
That's what I told the other fellas
and that's what I'm telling you.

446
00:25:39.290 --> 00:25:43.040
If he comes in. tell him to meet
Ben Reilly at The Alcove. 9:00 p.m.

447
00:25:43.040 --> 00:25:44.380
Tell him it's important.

448
00:25:44.380 --> 00:25:46.380
[upbeat jazz music playing]

449
00:25:59.680 --> 00:26:01.690
- [piano playing gentle jazz music]
- [indistinct chatter]

450
00:26:08.610 --> 00:26:10.610
Old Fashioned.

451
00:26:22.620 --> 00:26:24.130
[scoffs quietly]

452
00:26:28.710 --> 00:26:30.340
[emcee] Ladies and gentlemen.

453
00:26:30.340 --> 00:26:32.090
Cat Hardy.

454
00:26:32.090 --> 00:26:33.590
[applause]

455
00:26:38.810 --> 00:26:43.350
[Cat] <i>♪ Stars shining bright ♪</i>

456
00:26:43.350 --> 00:26:46.610
<i>♪ above you ♪</i>

457
00:26:47.980 --> 00:26:51.280
<i>♪ Night breezes seem to ♪</i>

458
00:26:52.820 --> 00:26:56.490
<i>♪ whisper. "I love you" ♪</i>

459
00:26:57.780 --> 00:27:00.120
<i>♪ Birds singing ♪</i>

460
00:27:00.120 --> 00:27:03.710
<i>♪ in the sycamore trees ♪</i>

461
00:27:06.380 --> 00:27:09.500
<i>♪ Dream a little dream ♪</i>

462
00:27:11.090 --> 00:27:14.380
<i>♪ of me... ♪</i>

463
00:27:14.380 --> 00:27:16.390
[band begins playing
"Dream a Little Dream of Me"]

464
00:27:17.470 --> 00:27:19.350
<i>♪ Say "Nighty-night" ♪</i>

465
00:27:19.350 --> 00:27:23.140
<i>♪ and kiss me ♪</i>

466
00:27:23.140 --> 00:27:24.640
<i>♪ Just hold me tight ♪</i>

467
00:27:24.640 --> 00:27:28.110
<i>♪ and tell me you'll miss me ♪</i>

468
00:27:29.190 --> 00:27:30.940
<i>♪ While I'm alone ♪</i>

469
00:27:30.940 --> 00:27:33.940
<i>♪ and blue as can be ♪</i>

470
00:27:33.940 --> 00:27:36.110
<i>♪ Dream a little dream ♪</i>

471
00:27:36.110 --> 00:27:39.870
<i>♪ of me ♪</i>

472
00:27:39.870 --> 00:27:41.620
<i>♪ Sweet dreams ♪</i>

473
00:27:41.620 --> 00:27:44.870
<i>♪ till sunbeams find you ♪</i>

474
00:27:44.870 --> 00:27:47.370
<i>♪ Sweet dreams that leave ♪</i>

475
00:27:47.380 --> 00:27:49.960
<i>♪ all worries behind you ♪</i>

476
00:27:49.960 --> 00:27:52.500
<i>♪ But in your dreams ♪</i>

477
00:27:52.510 --> 00:27:55.050
<i>♪ whatever they be ♪</i>

478
00:27:55.050 --> 00:27:57.010
<i>♪ Dream a little dream ♪</i>

479
00:27:57.010 --> 00:28:01.010
<i>♪ of me ♪</i>

480
00:28:01.010 --> 00:28:03.470
<i>♪ Quarter past ten and we're laughing ♪</i>

481
00:28:03.470 --> 00:28:05.890
<i>♪ It's the past tense of a daydream ♪</i>

482
00:28:05.890 --> 00:28:08.060
<i>♪ We'll go dancing under lights dim ♪</i>

483
00:28:08.060 --> 00:28:10.310
<i>♪ and it's past tense
when we say things ♪</i>

484
00:28:10.310 --> 00:28:12.770
<i>♪ From the dead of night
till the morning dew ♪</i>

485
00:28:12.780 --> 00:28:15.070
<i>♪ From the black and white
to the colorful ♪</i>

486
00:28:15.070 --> 00:28:17.070
<i>♪ If I'm not there. my belle ♪</i>

487
00:28:17.070 --> 00:28:19.660
<i>♪ dream me in a bow. make it beautiful ♪</i>

488
00:28:19.660 --> 00:28:22.870
<i>♪ We've been swimming ♪</i>

489
00:28:22.870 --> 00:28:28.080
<i>♪ in the usual ♪</i>

490
00:28:28.080 --> 00:28:32.040
<i>♪ but this deluge ♪</i>

491
00:28:32.040 --> 00:28:36.760
<i>♪ is delusional ♪</i>

492
00:28:36.760 --> 00:28:41.180
<i>♪ Dream of me. dream of me ♪</i>

493
00:28:41.180 --> 00:28:45.430
<i>♪ till I'm everything you see ♪</i>

494
00:28:45.430 --> 00:28:48.520
<i>♪ Dream of me ♪</i>

495
00:28:48.520 --> 00:28:53.190
<i>♪ dream of me till it's reality ♪</i>

496
00:28:53.190 --> 00:28:55.570
<i>♪ Don't dream too big ♪</i>

497
00:28:55.570 --> 00:28:59.860
<i>♪ just dream a little dream of me ♪</i>

498
00:28:59.860 --> 00:29:01.700
- [high-pitched ringing]
- <i>♪ I want you to dream ♪</i>

499
00:29:01.700 --> 00:29:03.660
<i>♪ a little dream of me ♪</i>

500
00:29:03.660 --> 00:29:07.040
<i>♪ Just a little tiny dream ♪</i>

501
00:29:07.040 --> 00:29:10.000
<i>♪ A little dream ♪</i>

502
00:29:10.000 --> 00:29:14.090
<i>♪ of me... ♪</i>

503
00:29:20.090 --> 00:29:22.140
- [applause]
- [man whoops]

504
00:29:23.850 --> 00:29:25.850
[band playing gentle jazz]

505
00:29:31.310 --> 00:29:33.310
[menacing music playing]

506
00:29:35.270 --> 00:29:36.690
[coin rattles]

507
00:29:38.530 --> 00:29:40.530
[line ringing]

508
00:29:41.660 --> 00:29:45.450
Damn it. Donegal. Where the hell are you?

509
00:29:45.450 --> 00:29:46.950
[Silvermane] Wake him up.

510
00:29:48.250 --> 00:29:49.750
Um...

511
00:29:51.710 --> 00:29:53.420
...that ain't gonna be so easy.

512
00:29:55.170 --> 00:29:56.670
He's dead.

513
00:29:58.170 --> 00:29:59.920
[Pudge] Told you I had a killer right.

514
00:29:59.920 --> 00:30:01.430
[giggles]

515
00:30:11.020 --> 00:30:13.770
[Donegal whimpers]

516
00:30:13.770 --> 00:30:15.440
Sorry. boss.

517
00:30:20.950 --> 00:30:22.490
Evening. friend.

518
00:30:22.490 --> 00:30:25.740
I'm not interested
in revenge or retribution.

519
00:30:25.740 --> 00:30:29.330
So I'm going to make this quick. Okay?

520
00:30:29.330 --> 00:30:31.330
[crying softly]

521
00:30:32.830 --> 00:30:35.830
Now. now. there's nothing to cry about.

522
00:30:35.830 --> 00:30:39.670
I'd just like to hear where Addison is.

523
00:30:43.090 --> 00:30:44.260
Do you know?

524
00:30:46.720 --> 00:30:48.680
Do you know?

525
00:30:48.680 --> 00:30:51.980
Uh. I shot him dead.

526
00:30:51.980 --> 00:30:55.190
He had some kind of crazy powers.

527
00:30:55.190 --> 00:30:57.980
- He burst into flames.
- [Silvermane] And what about

528
00:30:57.980 --> 00:31:01.110
the name of the man
who hired Addison to kill me?

529
00:31:02.490 --> 00:31:04.240
[whimpering] I. uh...

530
00:31:04.240 --> 00:31:06.110
I don't know.

531
00:31:06.120 --> 00:31:07.320
Fair enough.

532
00:31:11.620 --> 00:31:13.830
It's all over.

533
00:31:13.830 --> 00:31:15.540
It's done.

534
00:31:15.540 --> 00:31:17.830
[Donegal wheezes]

535
00:31:17.840 --> 00:31:19.550
[coughs]

536
00:31:32.310 --> 00:31:33.600
[Silvermane] Go to the morgue.

537
00:31:33.600 --> 00:31:35.640
Make sure Addison is really dead.

538
00:31:37.020 --> 00:31:38.860
And bring me the other private dick.

539
00:31:38.860 --> 00:31:41.400
Reilly?
He don't know any more than this guy.

540
00:31:41.400 --> 00:31:44.280
[Silvermane] Then he's got
nothing to worry about then. does he?

541
00:31:47.360 --> 00:31:49.370
- [indistinct chatter]
- [band playing gentle jazz]

542
00:31:56.210 --> 00:31:57.420
Do you mind?

543
00:31:58.500 --> 00:31:59.840
Please.

544
00:32:01.590 --> 00:32:03.670
I loved your performance.

545
00:32:03.670 --> 00:32:05.340
Thanks. doll.

546
00:32:05.340 --> 00:32:07.380
Is there somewhere we can talk?

547
00:32:07.380 --> 00:32:08.720
Here suits me.

548
00:32:08.720 --> 00:32:10.220
It's business.

549
00:32:10.220 --> 00:32:12.720
I wasn't aware we had any. Mister…?

550
00:32:12.720 --> 00:32:13.850
Reilly.

551
00:32:13.850 --> 00:32:16.480
It concerns your trip
to The Redcliff last night.

552
00:32:16.480 --> 00:32:17.890
Flint.

553
00:32:17.900 --> 00:32:20.520
Wh-- Now. I-I'm trying to help you.

554
00:32:20.520 --> 00:32:21.560
- I--
- [low growl]

555
00:32:21.570 --> 00:32:24.110
Mr. Reilly. I'd like you
to meet my friend. Flint Marko.

556
00:32:24.110 --> 00:32:26.110
- He's--
- A gorilla?

557
00:32:26.110 --> 00:32:27.820
Do you mind?

558
00:32:27.820 --> 00:32:31.070
- Slowly.
- Oh. the ape speaks. Incredible.

559
00:32:31.080 --> 00:32:32.910
I thought you might find that useful.

560
00:32:34.410 --> 00:32:36.580
- Everything. okay. Ms. Hardy?
- Yes.

561
00:32:36.580 --> 00:32:39.540
Mr. Reilly's a very nice man.
but he was just about to leave.

562
00:32:39.540 --> 00:32:41.580
- Who told you that?
- That you were leaving?

563
00:32:41.590 --> 00:32:44.090
- That I'm nice.
- Just a hunch.

564
00:32:44.090 --> 00:32:46.550
Maybe you can confirm it by leaving
without messing up Flint's tie.

565
00:32:46.550 --> 00:32:49.880
He really struggles with a double Windsor
and I just painted my nails.

566
00:32:49.890 --> 00:32:51.390
Sharpened 'em. too.

567
00:32:52.350 --> 00:32:53.850
And don't trouble yourself. Flint.

568
00:32:53.850 --> 00:32:56.850
I'm happy to make my exit
without either of your fists

569
00:32:56.850 --> 00:32:58.560
busting my eye sockets.

570
00:32:58.560 --> 00:33:01.150
Um. take another look at that
and perhaps tomorrow

571
00:33:01.150 --> 00:33:02.980
we can discuss the price of the negatives

572
00:33:02.980 --> 00:33:05.360
over lunch. I might even pay.

573
00:33:05.360 --> 00:33:08.570
seeing as I'm such a nice guy.

574
00:33:08.570 --> 00:33:10.450
I suppose you think you're pretty clever.

575
00:33:10.450 --> 00:33:12.450
No. actually. most days
I think I should just

576
00:33:12.450 --> 00:33:14.580
stick my head in the oven
and get it over with.

577
00:33:14.580 --> 00:33:15.580
Well. what's stopping you?

578
00:33:15.580 --> 00:33:17.330
Simple. I'm a coward.

579
00:33:25.750 --> 00:33:27.760
[tense music playing]

580
00:33:32.430 --> 00:33:34.890
Spare some change for a hungry orphan boy?

581
00:33:34.890 --> 00:33:37.100
I got to tail? White suit?

582
00:33:37.100 --> 00:33:39.520
Sure do. mister. Thanks.

583
00:34:01.460 --> 00:34:03.460
♪ ♪

584
00:34:20.730 --> 00:34:22.900
♪ ♪

585
00:34:42.500 --> 00:34:44.670
[Ben] Some view up here.

586
00:34:44.670 --> 00:34:47.210
You can see the lights
all the way from Jersey.

587
00:34:47.210 --> 00:34:49.380
[Flint] I'd like those negatives. please.

588
00:34:49.380 --> 00:34:51.010
[Ben] Cutting right to it. huh?

589
00:34:53.340 --> 00:34:55.180
You don't even want to catch your breath?

590
00:34:56.180 --> 00:34:58.720
Mister. despite what I do for a living.

591
00:34:58.720 --> 00:35:00.890
I really don't enjoy hurting people.

592
00:35:00.890 --> 00:35:02.560
Then don't.

593
00:35:02.560 --> 00:35:05.230
I know a terrific hamburger joint.
open all night.

594
00:35:05.230 --> 00:35:06.810
Let's sit. Talk it over.

595
00:35:08.320 --> 00:35:11.230
So you're not hungry. How about a drink?

596
00:35:11.240 --> 00:35:12.860
Last chance.

597
00:35:12.860 --> 00:35:14.570
Opium?

598
00:35:14.570 --> 00:35:15.490
[grunting]

599
00:35:20.080 --> 00:35:21.660
Why be stubborn?

600
00:35:21.660 --> 00:35:24.910
One way or another.
you're gonna give me those negatives.

601
00:35:24.920 --> 00:35:28.250
- It doesn't have to be like this.
- You're right. You could stop punching me.

602
00:35:30.880 --> 00:35:33.130
The negatives or I drop you.

603
00:35:36.970 --> 00:35:38.640
[chuckles] Well. the thing is...

604
00:35:38.640 --> 00:35:40.350
I'm not really scared of heights.

605
00:35:40.350 --> 00:35:41.640
[both grunting]

606
00:36:10.670 --> 00:36:12.170
[panting]

607
00:36:16.510 --> 00:36:17.930
[Flint grunting]

608
00:36:17.930 --> 00:36:19.590
[soft crumpling. shifting]

609
00:36:19.600 --> 00:36:21.600
[eerie music playing]

610
00:36:34.780 --> 00:36:36.860
Jesus...

611
00:36:36.860 --> 00:36:38.490
[grunting continuing]

612
00:36:45.120 --> 00:36:46.540
Flint?

613
00:36:46.540 --> 00:36:48.540
[grunting continuing]

614
00:37:02.010 --> 00:37:04.010
[low growling]

615
00:37:18.700 --> 00:37:20.780
[propulsive music playing]

616
00:37:20.780 --> 00:37:22.200
[grunting]

617
00:38:06.990 --> 00:38:08.290
[Ben grunts]

618
00:38:09.620 --> 00:38:11.160
[yelling]

619
00:38:14.960 --> 00:38:15.840
[sharp exhale]

620
00:38:16.960 --> 00:38:18.340
[grunting]

621
00:38:26.890 --> 00:38:28.890
[lift gears squeaking]

622
00:38:30.020 --> 00:38:31.270
[lift door opens]

623
00:38:31.270 --> 00:38:32.770
[Cat] Don't hurt him.

624
00:38:34.900 --> 00:38:37.360
- Where am I? Huh?
- Flint?

625
00:38:37.360 --> 00:38:39.230
Are you okay?

626
00:38:39.230 --> 00:38:40.740
What happened?

627
00:38:42.400 --> 00:38:44.200
What the hell is this?

628
00:38:44.200 --> 00:38:46.700
Just leave us alone. please.

629
00:38:51.120 --> 00:38:53.920
Here are the negatives. On the house.

630
00:38:58.380 --> 00:39:00.380
[plaintive music playing]

631
00:39:05.890 --> 00:39:06.970
[Janet] <i>I can't</i>

632
00:39:06.970 --> 00:39:10.510
believe you gave her the negatives.
And for free.

633
00:39:10.520 --> 00:39:11.850
Don't you think you're overreacting?

634
00:39:11.850 --> 00:39:13.180
No. Ben. [short chuckle]

635
00:39:13.190 --> 00:39:14.850
This is what reacting looks like.

636
00:39:14.850 --> 00:39:16.900
It's the physical response to a stimulus.

637
00:39:16.900 --> 00:39:19.320
You just haven't felt it in half a decade.

638
00:39:19.320 --> 00:39:22.190
That's actually my lamp.
My-my... my aunt gave it to me.

639
00:39:22.190 --> 00:39:23.440
You're afraid of the mob-- sure.

640
00:39:23.450 --> 00:39:25.240
Don't want to piss off the mayor-- fine.

641
00:39:25.240 --> 00:39:27.320
But a lounge singer?

642
00:39:27.320 --> 00:39:29.990
I told you. there were
extenuating circumstances.

643
00:39:29.990 --> 00:39:31.700
I have given you so much room.

644
00:39:31.700 --> 00:39:33.410
Airplanes have less runway.

645
00:39:33.410 --> 00:39:35.870
But at a certain point.
when someone tells you what they are.

646
00:39:35.870 --> 00:39:37.080
you have to listen.

647
00:39:37.080 --> 00:39:38.830
[Cat] And what is he?

648
00:39:38.840 --> 00:39:40.630
[sultry music playing]

649
00:39:40.630 --> 00:39:41.630
Retired.

650
00:39:43.510 --> 00:39:45.170
Cat Hardy.

651
00:39:45.180 --> 00:39:47.720
Uh. meet my secretary. Janet Ruiz.

652
00:39:47.720 --> 00:39:49.510
Ex-secretary. I just quit.

653
00:39:50.350 --> 00:39:53.180
Shame. I came here to offer him a job.

654
00:39:55.310 --> 00:39:56.640
My friend Flint--

655
00:39:56.650 --> 00:39:58.560
the one you met last night--

656
00:39:58.560 --> 00:40:00.360
he's disappeared.

657
00:40:02.110 --> 00:40:03.610
Fifty dollar retainer. up front.

658
00:40:03.610 --> 00:40:05.110
Then it's ten a day. plus expenses.

659
00:40:14.450 --> 00:40:16.460
[propulsive music playing]

660
00:40:18.420 --> 00:40:19.670
[grunts]

661
00:40:20.670 --> 00:40:23.340
My friend Flint--
the one you met last night?

662
00:40:24.260 --> 00:40:25.260
[grunts]

663
00:40:25.260 --> 00:40:26.340
[Cat] <i>He's disappeared.</i>

664
00:40:26.340 --> 00:40:27.510
[Flint panting]

665
00:40:27.510 --> 00:40:28.550
[Janet] <i>He turned into sand.</i>

666
00:40:28.550 --> 00:40:30.800
right?
Just seems like. kind of like a big deal.

667
00:40:32.430 --> 00:40:34.140
[Cat] <i>You're an investigator.</i>

668
00:40:34.140 --> 00:40:35.390
Investigate.

669
00:40:40.690 --> 00:40:42.190
[Janet] <i>She is hiding something.</i>

670
00:40:42.190 --> 00:40:44.860
You know. sometimes I think
you forget I do this for a living.

671
00:40:46.990 --> 00:40:48.280
- [The Spider] Oh. come on.
- [grunts]

672
00:40:48.280 --> 00:40:49.490
What the hell is going on?

673
00:40:49.490 --> 00:40:51.320
[Ben] <i>I can't get into it right now.</i>

674
00:40:51.320 --> 00:40:54.580
[Robbie] <i>Suddenly you're not the only guy
in New York with powers.</i>

675
00:40:54.580 --> 00:40:56.540
<i>and you can't get into it right now?</i>

676
00:40:56.540 --> 00:40:59.330
[Silvermane] <i>The Spider appears
to have forgotten who runs this town.</i>

677
00:41:00.290 --> 00:41:01.460
We've got a fight coming.

678
00:41:01.460 --> 00:41:03.040
I want you to help me.

679
00:41:03.750 --> 00:41:05.920
<i>We have a man nobody can stop.</i>

680
00:41:07.630 --> 00:41:09.260
[Leyden] <i>It's the best damn show</i>

681
00:41:09.260 --> 00:41:10.640
in town.

682
00:41:16.100 --> 00:41:18.230
- [bartender] <i>What about The Spider?</i>
- [man 1] <i>The Spider?</i>

683
00:41:18.230 --> 00:41:19.560
- [men laughing]
- [man 2] Yeah. right.

684
00:41:19.560 --> 00:41:22.440
Look. maybe... maybe. maybe. maybe

685
00:41:22.440 --> 00:41:24.770
The Spider is a guy like anyone else.

686
00:41:24.770 --> 00:41:26.360
You ever think about that?

687
00:41:30.410 --> 00:41:31.950
[Morris] <i>Crime is out of control.</i>

688
00:41:31.950 --> 00:41:33.490
<i>The city needs order.</i>

689
00:41:33.490 --> 00:41:34.700
[Robbie] <i>You have a choice.</i>

690
00:41:35.370 --> 00:41:36.750
You just have to make it.

691
00:41:39.660 --> 00:41:41.250
[grunting]

692
00:41:44.250 --> 00:41:46.760
[The Spider chuckles] Ah-cha-cha! Ha.

693
00:41:47.840 --> 00:41:49.720
Did you see that?

694
00:41:49.720 --> 00:41:52.340
I kicked them into kingdom co... [coughs]

695
00:41:52.340 --> 00:41:54.180
♪ ♪

696
00:41:54.180 --> 00:41:55.220
[gunfire]

697
00:41:56.260 --> 00:41:58.430
- [screaming]
- [grunting]

698
00:41:58.430 --> 00:42:01.560
[Ben] <i>This is a part of me
I wish never existed.</i>

699
00:42:04.770 --> 00:42:06.610
<i>Because with no power</i>

700
00:42:06.610 --> 00:42:08.610
<i>comes no responsibility.</i>

701
00:42:08.630 --> 00:42:10.630
you can find me on  and pless support me
https://www.youtube.com/@titoGamersHaven

702
00:42:11.400 --> 00:42:13.410
[intriguing music playing]

703
00:42:42.350 --> 00:42:44.350
♪ ♪

704
00:43:12.380 --> 00:43:14.380
♪ ♪

705
00:43:42.410 --> 00:43:44.410
♪ ♪

706
00:44:12.440 --> 00:44:14.440
♪ ♪
